31. Nullis auctoribus. According to Roman law a woman was never regarded as completely ⁶ sui iuris.' She was always ‘ In Potestate parentis‚’ or ‘In Manu viri,' or ‘In tutela! Hence, strictly speaking, she could perform no legal act without the sanction of her father. or of her husband, or of her guardian, as the case might be, and the person or persons who gave this sanction became ‘Auctor’ or ‘Aue- tores' of the transaction. Thus in the speech on the Lex Oppia, ascribed by Livy (34, 2,) to Cato —‘ Maiores nostri, nullam, ne privatam quidem, rem agere feminas sine auctore voluerunt: in manu esse parentum, fratrum, virorum.’—Here ‘nullis auctoribus’ implies that this marriage was not countenanced or graced by the presence of any of the relatives or friends of Sassia.
